Your code is simple, but the main issue here seems to be that you're creating a million-element vector on each run. Allocating large chunks of memory frequently can lead to performance bottlenecks in Rust due to cache misses and locking overhead. If you want better performance, it's often beneficial to avoid allocations or reuse existing buffers if possible.

Instead of using `vec!`, consider pre-allocating with a fixed size upfront like this:

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut data = vec![0_u32; 1_000_000];
    for i in 0..data.len() {
        data[i] = i as u32;
    }
}
```
But if you're reading large inputs, consider using a `VecDeque` or slices (`&mut [u32; 1_000_000]`) that avoid frequent allocations. Also, when profiling with tools like criterion, make sure to also profile the allocation overhead separately.

Good question! Rust provides great profiling tools. You can use the `criterion` crate to write benchmarks that isolate performance differences:

```rust
use criterion::{black_box, Criterion};

fn fill_vec(c: &mut Criterion) {
    c.bench_function("fill vec", |b| {
        b.to_block(|| {
            let mut data = Vec::with_capacity(1_000_000);
            for i in 0..black_box(data.capacity()) {
                data.push(i as u32);
            }
        })
    });
}

fn fill_vec_fixed_size(c: &mut Criterion) {
    let mut data = vec![0_u32; 1_000_000];
    c.bench_function("fill vec fixed size", |b| b.to_block(|| {
        for i in 0..black_box(data.len()) {
            data[i] = i as u32;
        }
    }));
}

fn main() {
    criterion_group!(benches, fill_vec, fill_vec_fixed_size);
    benches::main();
}
```
Then run with `cargo bench` and compare the times. That will give you concrete data on whether your pre-allocation strategy is paying off.

